### 3. NEGOTIATION FRAMEWORK\
\
#### Scenario Playbooks (6 exact scripts)\
\
**Scenario 1: "$400 is too much for a teardown"**\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  NEVER discount. Rescope.\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "What would this intelligence be worth if it changed a pricing decision or helped avoid a wrong product bet?" [PAUSE]\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  If they still push: "I can do top 3 competitors instead of 5 for $300. Same insights, narrower lens."\
\
**Scenario 2: "$1,500/mo is above our budget"**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "What range were you thinking? Not to match it \'97 to see if there's a scope that works."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  $800-1,200: Redirect to Starter at $1,000/mo\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  $300-500: Redirect to one-time Teardown ($400)\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "No budget": "It sounds like timing isn't right. I'll send you my LinkedIn insights \'97 reach out when it changes."\
\
**Scenario 3: "Let me think about it"**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "Of course. What specifically are you weighing \'97 scope, investment, timing, or something else?" [PAUSE \'97 surfaces real objection]\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "I need to check with my co-founder" 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "Want me to send a one-pager? I can join a 10-min call with both of you."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "Not sure it's worth it" 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "What would solving [their problem] be worth in time/money saved this quarter?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  ALWAYS leave with a concrete date: "Let's talk [specific day]." Calendar it immediately.\
\
**Scenario 4: "Can you do a free trial first?"**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "The Competitive Teardown IS the trial. Real project, real deliverable, low investment. If you love it, we talk retainer. If not, you still got something valuable."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "I can share a sample teardown I did for another market \'97 that shows format and quality. What I can't do is research YOUR market for free, because that research IS the product."\
\
**Scenario 5: Proposal silence (5+ days)**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D2: LinkedIn \'97 "Sent the proposal \'97 any questions?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D5: Email \'97 "One more thing I noticed after our call: [genuine new insight]. Updated proposal attached." (add value, don't chase)\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D8: Email \'97 "Is [original date] still realistic, or has the priority shifted?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D14: The Capacity Card \'97 "I have a new project starting [date] that'll take most of my capacity. If you'd like to move forward, this week would be ideal. If not, I can revisit when things free up."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D21+: Move to nurture. "All the best with [Company]. If competitive intelligence becomes a priority, I'm easy to find."\
\
**Scenario 6: Scope negotiation mid-engagement**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  Client wants to reduce scope but keep price:\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "Absolutely \'97 if scope is smaller, investment should match. That would be [lower tier] at $[price]. The $1,500 Standard includes [X,Y,Z]. If those aren't needed, $1,000 is the right fit."\
\
**7 Meta-Rules:**\
1. Never be first to name a number \'97 "What budget were you thinking?"\
2. Never discount \'97 rescope\
3. The person who needs the deal less, wins \'97 build enough pipeline that no deal is life-or-death\
4. Silence is your best tool \'97 state price, stop talking\
5. Always have a walk-away price (Teardown: $300 min; Retainer: $800/mo min)\
6. Frame as investment: "$400 that prevents a $20K pricing mistake" not "$400 cost"\
7. Create urgency with truth, not fabrication \'97 "I have limited capacity" is true\
