### Negotiation Framework\
\
#### Los 6 Escenarios + Scripts Exactos\
\
**Escenario 1: "Your price is too high" (pricing objection)**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "Completely fair \'97 what were you expecting to invest? [PAUSE \'97 let them talk]"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  If gap is small: "I can work with that if we tighten the scope slightly. What's the one deliverable you need most?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  If gap is large: "For that budget, I can do X [reduced version]. The full engagement at $[price] includes Y and Z which most clients say is where the real value is. Which makes more sense for where you are right now?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  NEVER: discount without reducing scope. Discounting trains them to always negotiate.\
\
**Escenario 2: "We don't have budget right now"**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "When does budget open up?" [PAUSE]\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  If Q2/Q3: "Let's put a 30-min call on the calendar for [specific date]. I'll share what I'm seeing in your market in the meantime \'97 no pressure."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  If vague: "Understood. In the meantime, let me send you a sample teardown so you can see exactly what you'd be getting. When it makes sense, you'll know what to expect."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  Log in HubSpot as "Nurture Q[X]" with follow-up date.\
\
**Escenario 3: "Let me think about it" / "I need to talk to my partner"**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "Of course \'97 what specifically would help you make the decision?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  If it's internal: "Who else would need to be comfortable with this? I'm happy to do a 15-min call with them too."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  Set specific follow-up: "When should I check back? Thursday or Friday this week?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  NEVER leave this without a date.\
\
**Escenario 4: "Can you do a free trial first?"**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "I understand the instinct \'97 you want to see the quality before committing. Here's what I suggest: the Competitive Teardown at $400 IS the trial. It's a complete, real deliverable. If it's not useful, you don't continue. That's lower risk than a 'free' month where we both have unclear expectations."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  Alternative: "I can do a Free Quick-Scan \'97 1 page, 3 competitors, your 3 biggest questions. I send it, you see the quality, we decide from there. No strings."\
\
**Escenario 5: Proposal sent, silence for 5+ days**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D5: Loom 60s \'97 "Recorded a quick walk-through of the proposal in case it's helpful to share internally." Send the link.\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D7: "Any questions I can answer, or does the scope need adjusting?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D10: "I have [date] blocked for your kickoff if we go ahead. Is that still realistic?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D14: "I have another client inquiry for this slot. Wanted to give you first right of refusal before I respond to them."\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  D21: "Closing this out \'97 no worries if timing isn't right. I'll check in next quarter."\
\
**Escenario 6: Scope negotiation mid-project**\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  Client asks for something outside scope:\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  "Happy to add that \'97 it's outside our current scope, so let me scope it quickly. [X hours at $Y/hr = $Z additional]. Want me to add it to this month or handle it as a separate invoice?"\

\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  NEVER: just do it without flagging. One "free" exception trains them to always ask.\
\
**7 Meta-Reglas de Negociaci\'f3n:**\
1. Always anchor high (Option A) \'97 it makes Option B (your target) look reasonable\
2. Never be the first to name a number if you can avoid it\
3. Silence is your friend \'97 after naming your price, shut up\
4. Reduce scope before reducing price, always\
5. Every concession needs a concession in return ("I can do X if you can do Y")\
6. "Let me check my calendar" buys time and signals demand\
7. You're selecting clients, not begging for them \'97 the energy matters\
